00:22:26,557 --> 00:22:28,998
And I may not have played your previous games.

501
00:22:29,318 --> 00:22:30,839
Start off giving me a little bit of background.

502
00:22:31,379 --> 00:22:33,660
Tell me what you've worked on before.

503
00:22:34,981 --> 00:22:36,962
Don't assume, and don't be offended in particular

504
00:22:37,002 --> 00:22:38,303
if I haven't played your game before,

505
00:22:38,423 --> 00:22:39,743
even if it was well received.

506
00:22:39,783 --> 00:22:40,944
There's a lot of stuff out there.

507
00:22:42,556 --> 00:22:46,219
Number 25, you get annoyed if I ask you questions.

508
00:22:47,341 --> 00:22:51,204
And this is hard sometimes because if you've pitched and

509
00:22:51,224 --> 00:22:52,946
you've rehearsed your pitch really well and you know

510
00:22:52,986 --> 00:22:54,668
exactly what you're going to say and you have your whole

511
00:22:54,688 --> 00:22:58,751
thing scripted and down, and then somebody like five

512
00:22:58,771 --> 00:23:00,853
minutes in raises their hand and asks you a question you're

513
00:23:00,873 --> 00:23:03,436
going to answer later on, it's really, really annoying.

514
00:23:04,197 --> 00:23:04,377
But.

515
00:23:05,380 --> 00:23:07,643
If somebody's asking you questions while you're pitching,

516
00:23:07,663 --> 00:23:09,184
it means they're interested in your game.

517
00:23:09,424 --> 00:23:10,786
And it means that they want to know more.

518
00:23:10,826 --> 00:23:14,690
And so try to roll with the flow of how the pitch goes.

519
00:23:15,370 --> 00:23:17,132
If it takes you off script, go off script.

520
00:23:18,874 --> 00:23:21,256
You're not being judged on how well you stick to script.

521
00:23:21,656 --> 00:23:22,938
It's how well you convey

522
00:23:23,238 --> 00:23:24,619
what needs to be conveyed for the game.

523
00:23:26,998 --> 00:23:27,778
This is a weird one.

524
00:23:27,838 --> 00:23:29,159
We're watching the pitch on your phone.

525
00:23:30,860 --> 00:23:32,921
It's really hard to look at a PowerPoint

526
00:23:33,001 --> 00:23:34,341
if it's like this big.

527
00:23:35,242 --> 00:23:38,183
And so, be sure you have the adequate technology

528
00:23:38,223 --> 00:23:39,063
to pitch what you're pitching.

529
00:23:39,824 --> 00:23:41,384
Even if you're pitching a phone game,

530
00:23:41,885 --> 00:23:44,506
it is often worthwhile to show stuff on a tablet

531
00:23:44,546 --> 00:23:45,766
to the person you're pitching to.

532
00:23:46,407 --> 00:23:51,649
So please, bring a tablet or a laptop to your pitch.

533
00:23:55,487 --> 00:23:57,548
Number 27, you bought a laptop, but you

534
00:23:57,568 --> 00:23:58,629
didn't bring headphones.

535
00:24:01,110 --> 00:24:02,071
I was talking to somebody.

536
00:24:02,111 --> 00:24:03,612
I no longer take pitches because I'm freelance.

537
00:24:03,652 --> 00:24:05,833
But somebody showed me their game a couple of days ago.

538
00:24:05,893 --> 00:24:07,795
And I thanked him because we were in a really noisy place,

539
00:24:07,835 --> 00:24:09,876
and he had headphones.

540
00:24:10,036 --> 00:24:11,677
Sound is at all important to your game.

541
00:24:11,697 --> 00:24:15,080
If it means anything, assume you're going to be pitching in

542
00:24:15,220 --> 00:24:16,921
the noisiest bar at GDC.

543
00:24:17,061 --> 00:24:18,582
Because a lot of times, that's what happens.

544
00:24:19,302 --> 00:24:21,184
And actually, please bring headphones.

545
00:24:21,264 --> 00:24:23,945
Because if you hand me your earbuds, I don't want to put

546
00:24:23,965 --> 00:24:24,546
them in my ears.

547
00:24:29,054 --> 00:24:31,035
Number 28, this only happened once.

548
00:24:33,256 --> 00:24:35,678
You show up hungover or drunk or high.

549
00:24:36,438 --> 00:24:37,199
Please don't do this.

550
00:24:39,040 --> 00:24:40,641
Hungover is probably the most common one,

551
00:24:40,821 --> 00:24:43,042
but I've seen the others.

552
00:24:44,563 --> 00:24:47,704
And it really, my immediate response

553
00:24:47,804 --> 00:24:49,766
is, if you're not taking this seriously,

554
00:24:50,006 --> 00:24:51,446
then why am I taking this?

555
00:24:52,647 --> 00:24:57,752
And it also suggests that if you're not able to pull it together for a half-hour pitch,

556
00:24:58,472 --> 00:25:03,056
what is it going to be like over the entire development?

557
00:25:03,536 --> 00:25:06,098
I've gotten the five-minute warning, but fortunately I only have two more.

558
00:25:08,052 --> 00:25:09,313
Don't trash other companies.

559
00:25:10,373 --> 00:25:12,674
People will say, oh yeah, our last publisher

560
00:25:12,694 --> 00:25:14,936
was really awful, or we really hated him,

561
00:25:15,096 --> 00:25:16,876
or we don't want to make a game like this other game

562
00:25:16,896 --> 00:25:19,398
because it's crap, or don't do this.

563
00:25:19,518 --> 00:25:20,438
Don't trash other people.

564
00:25:20,458 --> 00:25:22,739
There's ways to talk about why your game is great,

565
00:25:23,420 --> 00:25:25,781
or why you're a great team without talking

566
00:25:25,861 --> 00:25:28,262
about negative things about other people in the industry.

567
00:25:29,082 --> 00:25:31,785
Because again, development relationships

568
00:25:31,805 --> 00:25:32,886
are always very stressful,

569
00:25:33,286 --> 00:25:36,529
and what will run through the publisher's mind is,

570
00:25:36,949 --> 00:25:38,070
how are they going to talk about us

571
00:25:38,591 --> 00:25:40,392
when they're making a game for us?

572
00:25:41,693 --> 00:25:43,675
And finally, make sure you take a shower.

573
00:25:45,617 --> 00:25:47,098
I shouldn't have to tell people this,

574
00:25:47,198 --> 00:25:48,319
and I know it's hard at GDC.

575
00:25:48,339 --> 00:25:49,640
You're walking around a lot,

576
00:25:50,321 --> 00:25:53,604
but I've tried not to hold it against people,

577
00:25:53,964 --> 00:25:54,184
but...

578
00:25:55,744 --> 00:25:56,004
Yeah.

579
00:25:57,406 --> 00:26:00,710
And this goes into the, if you're doing a VR demonstration,

580
00:26:00,791 --> 00:26:03,234
please wipe off the face plate before you give it

581
00:26:03,254 --> 00:26:04,395
to me to put on.

582
00:26:04,415 --> 00:26:05,637
Or don't give me your earbuds.

583
00:26:06,077 --> 00:26:08,520
Be mindful of the fact that we're talking and interacting

584
00:26:08,560 --> 00:26:09,281
with a lot of people.

585
00:26:09,482 --> 00:26:11,664
And it's a small thing, but it goes a long way

586
00:26:11,684 --> 00:26:14,047
to feeling like you respect the person you're pitching to.

587
00:26:15,690 --> 00:26:17,433
So just a couple of positive things at the end,

588
00:26:17,453 --> 00:26:18,795
because that was a whole lot of negativity.

589
00:26:19,776 --> 00:26:20,617
Be enthusiastic.

590
00:26:20,737 --> 00:26:21,759
Be excited about your game.

591
00:26:21,779 --> 00:26:23,822
You're the person who's the most excited about your game.

592
00:26:23,842 --> 00:26:25,384
And if you're not excited about your game,

593
00:26:25,724 --> 00:26:27,146
then who is going to be?

594
00:26:27,306 --> 00:26:28,808
Show that enthusiasm while you're pitching.

595
00:26:29,369 --> 00:26:30,250
Be upfront and honest.

596
00:26:30,290 --> 00:26:31,292
If you're an inexperienced team.

597
00:26:32,333 --> 00:26:33,394
Be sure to say that.

598
00:26:33,474 --> 00:26:36,675
You're not going to be able to fool most people you're pitching to.

599
00:26:36,695 --> 00:26:37,596
You're not going to be able to snow them.

600
00:26:37,616 --> 00:26:40,497
They've seen things many, many times.

601
00:26:41,258 --> 00:26:43,079
Be up front with what's hard about your development.

602
00:26:43,139 --> 00:26:46,741
Be up front about what your challenges are, what your risks are.

603
00:26:47,161 --> 00:26:48,982
That makes it seem like you know what you're doing

604
00:26:49,022 --> 00:26:51,103
when you're up front about the problems you face.

605
00:26:51,744 --> 00:26:53,344
Sell your hook really, really hard.

606
00:26:53,544 --> 00:26:56,126
What is it about your game that makes it original and unique

607
00:26:56,166 --> 00:26:56,626
and different?

608
00:26:56,666 --> 00:26:58,347
Because that's the thing that will make it sell.

609
00:26:58,887 --> 00:27:01,208
And above all, know your scope backwards and forwards.

610
00:27:01,288 --> 00:27:03,450
Know how much it's going to cost, how many levels,

611
00:27:03,510 --> 00:27:06,351
how many hours, how many characters, how much dialogue.

612
00:27:06,671 --> 00:27:08,792
You don't need to have created all these things.

613
00:27:09,072 --> 00:27:11,374
You need to know how many of each one of these things

614
00:27:11,734 --> 00:27:13,755
you're planning to have in your finished game.

615
00:27:15,776 --> 00:27:16,596
And I have like three minutes.

616
00:27:16,896 --> 00:27:18,297
So thank you very much.

617
00:27:25,455 --> 00:27:25,935
This is me.

618
00:27:26,495 --> 00:27:27,656
As I said, I'm no longer with Sony.

619
00:27:27,856 --> 00:27:31,317
I left Sony this past fall to go freelance as a design consultant.

620
00:27:32,057 --> 00:27:33,997
My website is gameontherails.com.

621
00:27:34,057 --> 00:27:38,759
You can follow me on Twitter at BBEpton, or you can just e-mail me if you have questions.

622
00:27:39,319 --> 00:27:43,980
And I think we probably have time for, like, two or three questions, if anybody has any.

623
00:27:44,440 --> 00:27:47,061
And they've asked me to ask people to come to the microphones, please,

624
00:27:47,681 --> 00:27:49,742
and please speak into the microphones because it's being recorded.

625
00:27:52,104 --> 00:27:56,087
Could you talk a little bit about time, about how much time people would budget for a pitch?

626
00:27:57,008 --> 00:27:59,150
Typically, when we were doing pitches, half an hour.

627
00:27:59,690 --> 00:28:04,475
Again, it depends. If we were doing a pitch at GDC, we'd assume it would be half an hour.

628
00:28:04,975 --> 00:28:07,978
If we were going on site, which would happen sometimes, that's going to be longer.

629
00:28:08,378 --> 00:28:13,182
We might spend an hour or two hours, but usually if you do a site visit, then you're actually

630
00:28:13,222 --> 00:28:17,265
digging into what sort of tools are they using.

631
00:28:17,805 --> 00:28:21,148
The pitch itself might still only take half an hour, but then there'd be all sorts of

632
00:28:21,188 --> 00:28:21,968
follow-up questions.

633
00:28:22,509 --> 00:28:28,933
So in general, have something, your high-level elevator pitch, but if you're doing a PowerPoint

634
00:28:28,973 --> 00:28:30,434
presentation, 30 minutes is good.

635
00:28:32,459 --> 00:28:40,084
Hi, I'm from Lebanon and the Arab world in general is a publisher-light, investor-heavy industry.

636
00:28:40,784 --> 00:28:44,347
So we tend to be pitching studios more than we do individual games.

637
00:28:45,728 --> 00:28:48,930
What approach, what advice can you give in terms of that?

638
00:28:48,970 --> 00:28:51,491
I know it's not something you have experience with necessarily.

639
00:28:52,158 --> 00:28:56,920
Yeah, so if I understand your question, it's like, how do you pitch to investors as opposed to publishers? Is that correct?

640
00:28:57,060 --> 00:28:58,361
Studios rather than games.

641
00:28:58,681 --> 00:29:00,621
Oh, studios rather than games.

642
00:29:01,021 --> 00:29:11,025
So, in general, I have a longer version of this talk that's an hour and I can't fit everything in, but if you can gauge who's in the room right at the very beginning...

643
00:29:12,485 --> 00:29:14,386
If you have senior management, then you

644
00:29:14,426 --> 00:29:17,127
want to talk about high-level vision and capabilities

645
00:29:17,167 --> 00:29:17,587
of the team.

646
00:29:18,107 --> 00:29:20,087
So this is the grand thing we want to build,

647
00:29:20,247 --> 00:29:24,328
and this is why we're great and why we can execute on it.

648
00:29:24,809 --> 00:29:26,489
If you are talking to people who are,

649
00:29:26,769 --> 00:29:29,270
if you have a designer in the room or an engineer

650
00:29:29,290 --> 00:29:31,430
or an artist, my job is to go along as the designer

651
00:29:31,450 --> 00:29:32,271
and evaluate the design.

652
00:29:32,791 --> 00:29:36,032
Then that's why you go lower and more into the nitty gritty.

653
00:29:36,432 --> 00:29:38,772
So what I'm saying, for your case,

654
00:29:38,792 --> 00:29:40,753
where you're pitching the studio.

655
00:29:41,193 --> 00:29:43,235
What you really want to be doing is pitching the capabilities.

656
00:29:43,815 --> 00:29:46,918
So you want to be saying, here's the people we have.

657
00:29:47,378 --> 00:29:50,400
Here are what they're able to do.

658
00:29:50,481 --> 00:29:51,521
If they've worked on other games,

659
00:29:51,561 --> 00:29:52,883
these are the other games they've worked on.

660
00:29:53,403 --> 00:29:55,665
And then talk about your creative vision,

661
00:29:55,705 --> 00:29:57,907
your high level, this is the grand thing

662
00:29:57,947 --> 00:29:58,747
we want to accomplish.

663
00:29:58,787 --> 00:30:02,130
Not necessarily with one game, but with multiple games.

664
00:30:02,150 --> 00:30:03,871
This is thematically what we want to do,

665
00:30:04,252 --> 00:30:05,893
or this is in business terms what we want to do.

666
00:30:06,053 --> 00:30:06,794
That's how I'd approach that.

667
00:30:08,434 --> 00:30:15,505
Oh, thank you. Just a quick question. I went to Game Connection America this year and well, even though

668
00:30:16,587 --> 00:30:23,932
according to the 30 dots over there, we pretty much cover everything. But at the same time,

669
00:30:24,092 --> 00:30:30,957
since we don't have any published games, we sort of hit a wall where people were always,

670
00:30:31,057 --> 00:30:36,260
yeah, I cannot finance you because you don't have anything published. So do you have any

671
00:30:36,300 --> 00:30:39,202
sort of recommendations for people who are starting from scratch?

672
00:30:43,396 --> 00:30:46,119
The question was how do you get published when you're starting from scratch?

673
00:30:46,399 --> 00:30:52,044
The challenge there is that it's on the can this team execute front, because they don't

674
00:30:52,064 --> 00:30:54,286
want to take the risk, because they don't believe that you can pull it off.

675
00:30:55,487 --> 00:30:57,288
In that case, a lot of what you may need to do

676
00:30:57,929 --> 00:30:59,490
is put extra effort into your prototype.

677
00:30:59,930 --> 00:31:03,473
And that, unfortunately, means spending more money up front

678
00:31:03,593 --> 00:31:06,034
to show that you're capable of producing something

679
00:31:07,055 --> 00:31:08,116
that's, you know, 30% finished

680
00:31:09,036 --> 00:31:11,398
before you actually go to pitch it.

681
00:31:12,078 --> 00:31:14,460
It's very hard to pitch just a straight-up idea

682
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:17,762
if nobody on your team has a track record of delivering.

683
00:31:18,202 --> 00:31:19,743
The further along you get in your prototype

684
00:31:19,763 --> 00:31:21,344
and the more complete the prototype it is,

685
00:31:21,424 --> 00:31:23,566
the easier it is to sell with an inexperienced team.

686
00:31:24,126 --> 00:31:26,628
That's one reason as an inexperienced team to try to do something really small.

687
00:31:27,068 --> 00:31:31,350
Because then you can sell something that is more nearly complete when you're proposing it to somebody.

688
00:31:31,911 --> 00:31:32,231
Thank you.

689
00:31:33,472 --> 00:31:37,974
You say what you need to do while you're in your pitch, pitching your game,

690
00:31:38,515 --> 00:31:47,000
but what's the best way to get a certain company or people to actually be willing to meet with you to pitch your game to them?

691
00:31:49,191 --> 00:31:50,812
Contact them before you come to GDC.

692
00:31:50,832 --> 00:31:51,672
This was a big one.

693
00:31:52,633 --> 00:31:59,316
So research companies, a lot of times it's going to be hard to convince them to do any sort of travel

694
00:31:59,396 --> 00:32:02,458
or that you're going to do any sort of travel if you're pitching completely cold.

695
00:32:03,418 --> 00:32:07,100
A lot of times the way pitches would come in to us would be there would be an initial

696
00:32:07,160 --> 00:32:12,023
contact point, and because we were a publisher, we would advertise, you know, this is who

697
00:32:12,043 --> 00:32:12,923
you need to contact.

698
00:32:14,104 --> 00:32:19,086
Right to the initial contact point, it explained that you have, that you're a small company,

699
00:32:19,266 --> 00:32:23,709
there is a game that you're interested in pitching, and at that point you include basic

700
00:32:23,749 --> 00:32:26,670
information that shows that it's even worthwhile to take the pitch.

701
00:32:27,350 --> 00:32:31,493
At that point, typically what we would get might be one or

702
00:32:31,553 --> 00:32:34,655
two, three pages about what the intended game is.

703
00:32:34,715 --> 00:32:38,118
That's just a very high level concept description.

704
00:32:38,598 --> 00:32:40,919
And then more information on who the team is.

705
00:32:41,020 --> 00:32:43,421
Because again, the two questions are, is this

706
00:32:43,461 --> 00:32:44,062
worthwhile?

707
00:32:46,403 --> 00:32:48,545
Is this team able to execute?

708
00:32:48,885 --> 00:32:52,208
And so setting up front like, hey, I'm teasing you with

709
00:32:52,248 --> 00:32:53,749
something, you think you'd be interested in seeing this?

710
00:32:54,130 --> 00:32:55,731
Look at us, we're actually kind of competent.

711
00:32:55,771 --> 00:32:57,573
You should actually maybe trust us to do this.

712
00:32:58,173 --> 00:33:00,875
That, for us, was enough to at least get us to do a follow-up

713
00:33:00,956 --> 00:33:04,298
email, a little back and forth, and then try to do that

714
00:33:04,519 --> 00:33:06,460
prior to GDC or E3 or.

715
00:33:08,802 --> 00:33:13,524
Try to do it in a way that gives you a quick and easy meeting with somebody without it

716
00:33:13,584 --> 00:33:18,586
turning into travel expenses because nobody is going to pay for travel expenses for anything

717
00:33:18,606 --> 00:33:20,647
that's at the early, early proposal stage.

718
00:33:24,160 --> 00:33:28,605
My question is about trailers because I assume you get to see a lot of trailers in Flightliner work.

719
00:33:30,146 --> 00:33:34,150
When you watch trailers, how much patience do you have to watch them?

720
00:33:35,091 --> 00:33:40,056
And what elements are, let's say, more interesting or more relevant to you?

721
00:33:40,076 --> 00:33:43,860
Do you like to see gameplay? Do you like to see a narrated, hard-sale type of trailer?

722
00:33:44,301 --> 00:33:45,182
What's most effective?

723
00:33:46,687 --> 00:33:50,449
If you're pitching to investors or higher level management,

724
00:33:50,549 --> 00:33:52,330
a trailer can be really good for it

725
00:33:52,410 --> 00:33:53,490
because it's pretty and shiny.

726
00:33:54,291 --> 00:33:57,452
And it sort of shows off your ability to polish.

727
00:33:57,492 --> 00:33:59,493
If you're pitching to people that

728
00:33:59,533 --> 00:34:02,715
are more down in the trenches, they'll

729
00:34:02,735 --> 00:34:03,575
tend to ignore the trailer.

730
00:34:04,255 --> 00:34:07,097
I was more interested in prototype and in concept art

731
00:34:07,117 --> 00:34:08,838
than a trailer because you can hide

732
00:34:08,898 --> 00:34:10,298
so many things in a trailer.

733
00:34:11,259 --> 00:34:12,419
And so what I would say is that.

734
00:34:15,616 --> 00:34:20,398
Unless a trailer is something you can do very easily based on an existing prototype you have,

735
00:34:20,938 --> 00:34:25,740
an existing art you have, that's probably not the best place to put a lot of effort into your pitch.

736
00:34:26,040 --> 00:34:32,063
Because it will sell the game potentially to an inexperienced investor,

737
00:34:32,523 --> 00:34:37,365
but not to somebody who is really going to be digging deep into whether the game is going to be viable or not.

738
00:34:37,966 --> 00:34:38,246
Thank you.

739
00:34:39,786 --> 00:34:43,728
Are there any metrics that you think are important to bring to a pitch if you have them, or any you'd avoid?

740
00:34:45,513 --> 00:34:46,435
What do you mean by metrics?

741
00:34:46,495 --> 00:34:50,160
Like daily active users or previous sales on previous games or...

742
00:34:50,300 --> 00:34:50,741
Oh, absolutely.

743
00:34:50,761 --> 00:34:55,707
I mean, if you have a track record, and particularly if you have a track record of success, that

744
00:34:55,767 --> 00:34:58,892
is absolutely something that you should talk about.

745
00:34:59,693 --> 00:35:01,875
As I said, I have a longer version of this talk

746
00:35:01,895 --> 00:35:02,896
that is not entirely negative,

747
00:35:02,936 --> 00:35:05,899
and I talk about how to sell your company,

748
00:35:05,939 --> 00:35:06,540
and one thing is,

749
00:35:07,020 --> 00:35:08,582
who are the principal people in your company?

750
00:35:08,622 --> 00:35:09,703
What are their experiences?

751
00:35:09,763 --> 00:35:10,824
What games have you shipped?

752
00:35:10,864 --> 00:35:12,025
If those games have been successful,

753
00:35:12,085 --> 00:35:13,186
how successful were they?

754
00:35:13,606 --> 00:35:14,728
All that stuff is great,

755
00:35:14,828 --> 00:35:17,590
because that really shows that you're able to execute

756
00:35:17,771 --> 00:35:19,152
on what you're proposing.

757
00:35:19,212 --> 00:35:20,874
So yeah, if you have stuff like that,

758
00:35:21,875 --> 00:35:23,897
that's perfect information.

759
00:35:24,037 --> 00:35:24,237
Thanks.

760
00:35:28,565 --> 00:35:30,627
Sometimes when you have been working on a game for a long time,

761
00:35:30,647 --> 00:35:34,011
it's difficult for you to find back to the hook of the game.

762
00:35:34,071 --> 00:35:37,134
Do you have any tools to like finding back to the hook

763
00:35:37,174 --> 00:35:38,676
and defining the hook for a game?

764
00:35:39,497 --> 00:35:40,758
I'm not sure I understand your question.

765
00:35:41,760 --> 00:35:42,741
The hook of the game.

766
00:35:43,141 --> 00:35:43,622
Oh, the hook.

767
00:35:43,662 --> 00:35:44,342
How to find the hook?

768
00:35:45,663 --> 00:35:49,066
Well, that's the $20 million question, isn't it?

769
00:35:49,667 --> 00:35:53,951
Yeah, I mean, so what I tend to do as a designer,

770
00:35:53,991 --> 00:35:56,153
and this is outside pitching and designing,

771
00:35:56,273 --> 00:35:56,533
is that

772
00:35:58,294 --> 00:36:07,236
Take whatever your core game is and then push it off axis a little bit and see where that takes you.

773
00:36:07,856 --> 00:36:10,376
I'll use the first big game I worked on, which is Rainbow Six.

774
00:36:10,857 --> 00:36:17,538
We knew we wanted to do a first-person shooter, but we wanted it to have a slightly different feel.

775
00:36:18,518 --> 00:36:24,060
The hook started out with the idea that what would it be like to play a shooter where twitch reflexes didn't matter,

776
00:36:24,600 --> 00:36:27,040
where it was all about patience and tactics.

777
00:36:28,001 --> 00:36:30,002
And that came out almost from the very beginning,

778
00:36:30,042 --> 00:36:31,984
but it was the idea that we took something that was established

779
00:36:32,384 --> 00:36:33,385
and then said, oh, let's just take...

780
00:36:33,805 --> 00:36:35,466
What if we change the rules a little

781
00:36:35,506 --> 00:36:36,907
and push it a little in this direction?

782
00:36:37,287 --> 00:36:38,808
Or push it a little in that direction?

783
00:36:38,828 --> 00:36:40,890
There are a variety of things that can be a hook.

784
00:36:40,950 --> 00:36:42,771
I mean, a mechanic hook is always good.

785
00:36:42,791 --> 00:36:44,952
Sometimes just the look of a game is a hook.

786
00:36:45,673 --> 00:36:47,614
One of the best pitches we ever took at Sony

787
00:36:47,634 --> 00:36:49,075
was for The Unfinished Swan,

788
00:36:49,796 --> 00:36:51,897
and it was so stunning because it had an original mechanic

789
00:36:52,017 --> 00:36:53,458
and an original look at the same time,

790
00:36:53,478 --> 00:36:54,479
which was like two hooks.

791
00:36:54,919 --> 00:36:56,180
and two that were interrelated.

792
00:36:56,680 --> 00:36:59,222
And so, if you have a really compelling character,

793
00:36:59,322 --> 00:37:01,984
if you have a really original look,

794
00:37:02,044 --> 00:37:04,346
if you have a original gameplay twist,

795
00:37:04,826 --> 00:37:07,028
but look at ways to take something that already exists

796
00:37:07,228 --> 00:37:08,909
and push it in an unexpected direction

797
00:37:09,129 --> 00:37:11,210
and see where it takes you and iterate on that.

798
00:37:11,351 --> 00:37:13,032
Don't just pick the first one that comes to mind.

799
00:37:13,452 --> 00:37:14,353
Try to find different ways

800
00:37:14,433 --> 00:37:16,894
to push things in different directions.

801
00:37:17,335 --> 00:37:18,075
Thank you. Sure.

802
00:37:18,095 --> 00:37:21,097
Is anybody else?

803
00:37:21,938 --> 00:37:22,618
Okay, perfect.

